Myocardial infarction due to intracoronary thrombi without significant coronary artery disease in systemic lupus erythematosus.
 Acute myocardial infarction is a potentially fatal complication of SLE.
 Reported mechanisms include atherosclerosis, arteritis and coronary arterial spasm.
 The following case report presents a fourth possible cause; intracoronary thrombus with angiographically normal coronary arteries in a patient with active lupus and AMI.
